
## Objective
The goal of this level was to gain access to the Bandit26 account and obtain the password for the next level.

A private SSH key for Bandit26 was provided, but logging in normally did not give access to a shell. Instead, the connection immediately closed after displaying some text. The challenge was to understand why this happened and find a way to escape into a usable shell.

---

## Commands Used

### 1. Listing files in the home directory

Command:

ls -la

Purpose:

This command was used to identify useful files in the home directory. It revealed the presence of the private SSH key:

bandit26.sshkey

which would be used for authentication as Bandit26.

---

### 2. Connecting to Bandit26 using the SSH key

Command:

ssh -i bandit26.sshkey bandit26@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220

Purpose:

This command authenticated as Bandit26 using the provided private key.

Command Breakdown:

- ssh → Starts an SSH connection.
- -i bandit26.sshkey → Specifies the private key to use.
- bandit26@bandit.labs.overthewire.org → Connect as user Bandit26.
- -p 2220 → Connect using Bandit's SSH port.

The login succeeded, but the connection immediately closed.

---

### 3. Inspecting Bandit26's login shell

Command:

cat /etc/passwd | grep bandit26

Purpose:

This command was used to identify the shell assigned to Bandit26.

The output showed that Bandit26 was not using a normal Bash shell. Instead, it was configured to run a custom program:

/usr/bin/showtext

This explained why the session terminated immediately after login.

---

### 4. Understanding the custom shell

Command:

cat /usr/bin/showtext

Purpose:

This command was used to inspect the custom shell script.

The script displayed a text file using the `more` pager and then exited.

Understanding this behavior was the key to solving the level.

---

### 5. Resizing the terminal

Action:

Reduce the terminal height before connecting.

Purpose:

The `more` command only pauses when the content exceeds the available screen space.

By making the terminal window smaller, the displayed text could not fit on one screen, causing `more` to remain active instead of exiting immediately.

---

### 6. Opening the file in vi

Key Press:

v

Purpose:

While inside the `more` pager, pressing `v` opens the displayed file in the `vi` editor.

This provided an opportunity to escape the restricted environment.

---

### 7. Configuring vi to use Bash

Command inside vi:

:set shell=/bin/bash

Purpose:

This changed the shell that vi would use when spawning a command shell.

Instead of using the restricted environment, vi would launch Bash.

---

### 8. Escaping into a shell

Command inside vi:

:shell

Purpose:

This command spawned an interactive Bash shell from inside vi.

This bypassed the restricted login shell and provided normal command execution.

---

### 9. Reading the password

Command:

cat /etc/bandit_pass/bandit26

Purpose:

Once a Bash shell was obtained, this command displayed the password for the next level.

---

## Why the Solution Worked

The key concept in this level was understanding that authentication and shell access are separate things.

The SSH key successfully authenticated as Bandit26, but Bandit26's login shell was configured as:

/usr/bin/showtext

instead of:

/bin/bash

The custom shell displayed a text file using the `more` pager and then exited.

By shrinking the terminal window, `more` was forced to pause. While inside `more`, it was possible to launch `vi` using the `v` shortcut.

The `vi` editor allows users to spawn a shell. By configuring vi to use Bash and executing `:shell`, a normal shell was obtained, bypassing the restrictions imposed by the custom login shell.

This shell provided access to the Bandit26 password file.

---

## Linux Concepts / Commands Learned

### 1. SSH Key Authentication

SSH can authenticate using a private/public key pair instead of passwords.

The private key:

bandit26.sshkey

proved identity and allowed login as Bandit26.

---

### 2. Login Shells

Every Linux user has a shell assigned in `/etc/passwd`.

Common examples:

/bin/bash
/bin/sh
/bin/zsh

Bandit26 used:

/usr/bin/showtext

which caused a custom program to run after login.

---

### 3. Restricted Environments

A user may authenticate successfully but still be prevented from accessing a normal shell.

Restricted shells are commonly used to limit user actions.

This level demonstrated how a restricted environment can sometimes be bypassed through unintended functionality.

---

### 4. The `more` Pager

The `more` command is used to view long files one page at a time.

Unlike `cat`, it pauses when the content exceeds the terminal size.

The level relied on this behavior to keep the session active.

---

### 5. Terminal Dimensions

Many terminal programs behave differently depending on the size of the terminal window.

Reducing the terminal height forced `more` to remain active, making the escape possible.

---

### 6. Vi Editor Shell Escape

The `vi` editor can execute shell commands.

Useful commands:

:set shell=/bin/bash

Changes the shell used by vi.

:shell

Launches an interactive shell.

This capability allowed the restricted environment to be bypassed.

---

## Summary

This level focused on understanding the difference between authentication and shell access.

Although the SSH key successfully authenticated as Bandit26, the account used a custom login shell that immediately terminated the session. By analyzing the login shell, understanding how the `more` pager behaved, and using a shell escape through `vi`, it was possible to obtain a normal Bash shell and read the password for the next level.

Key concepts learned:

- SSH key authentication
- Login shells
- Restricted environments
- The `more` pager
- Terminal sizing effects
- Shell escapes through `vi`
- Privilege and access control in Linux
